\par This dialogue allows you to enter an arbitrary Universal (Greenwich Mean) date and time and see the Julian date corresponding to that moment.  The Julian date is updated dynamically as you change the Universal time.  Click OK to have Moontool display the 
situation at the specified Universal time (doing this will halt automatic updates; select Options/Run to resume them).  Clicking Now resets the Universal time to the current date and time. 
\par 
\par Moontool's ability to display the Moon's phase at any moment in history lets you quickly answer questions such as that posed in the April 1992 issue of }{\i\f7\fs20 Sky & Telescope}{\f7\fs20 
 (page 437): did Paul Revere's midnight ride really occur under the full Moon, or did Longfellow add the Moon to his poem purely for atmosphere?  Entering the time and date of Revere's ride: 05:00:00 UTC April 19th, 1775, in the Set Universal time panel, 
we find the Moon was 87% full that night, waning from the last full Moon at 21:53 UTC on April 15th, 1775.  Moontool tells us that the Moon was indeed close to full that night, confirming Revere's own recollection that "the Moon shone bright".
\par 
\par If you use this dialogue as a "Julian date calculator", be sure to remember that Julian dates change at noon Greenwich time rather than midnight.
\par 
\par You can enter dates as far back as Julian day 0, January 1, -4712 and as far into the future as you wish.  Note that astronomers and historians use different conventions for years before 1 }{\scaps\f7\fs20 a.d.}{\f7\fs20 
  In history books, the year that preceded 1 }{\scaps\f7\fs20 a.d.}{\f7\fs20  is called 1 }{\scaps\f7\fs20 b.c.}{\f7\fs20 ; zero not having come into use in European culture at the time.  Astronomers consider the year before 1 }{\scaps\f7\fs20 a.d.}{
\f7\fs20  as "year 0".  Thus when an astronomer talks about an eclipse having occurred in the year -412, that's the year historians refer to as "413 }{\scaps\f7\fs20 b.c.}{\f7\fs20 
".  In converting historical dates to Julian days, Moontool assumes the canonical date for the adoption of the Gregorian calendar, Friday, October 15th, 1582.  Many countries shifted to the Gregorian calendar much later; in Great Britain, not until 1752. 
 When investigating events in history, make sure you express all dates after October 15th, 1582 in the }{\i\f7\fs20 Gregorian}{\f7\fs20  calendar.
\par 
\par To convert a Julian date to Universal time, use the }{\f7\fs20\uldb Options/Set Julian date}{\v\f7\fs20 Setjdate}{\f7\fs20  dialogue.
